#Text=Henry Scobell
#Text=For the governor of Cape Cod , see Henry Jenner Scobell .
#Text=An 1884 drawing of what the Old Palace of Westminster ( destroyed by fire in 1834 ) , looked like in the time of Henry VIII when it was the seat of the Parliament of England
#Text=Henry Scobell ( baptised 1610 ; died 1660 ) [ 1 ] was an English Parliamentary official , and editor of official publications .
#Text=He was clerk to the Long Parliament , and wrote on parliamentary procedure and precedents .
#Text=Life

#Text=The title page of Memorials of the Method and Manner of Proceedings in Parliament in Passing Bills ( 3rd ed . , 1670 ) , [ 2 ] written by " H.S. E. C.P. " ( Henry Scobell , Esquire , Clerk of Parliament )
#Text=Initially under-clerk of the parliaments , Scobell became Clerk of the House of Commons from 5 January 1649 , his predecessor Henry Elsynge having resigned .
#Text=Scobell also held a position as censor of publications , and then was Clerk of the Parliament for life with effect from 14 May 1649 . [ 3 ]
#Text=He was the first editor , from 9 October 1649 , of Severall Proceedings in Parliament , an early official newspaper , and the second of Parliament 's publications . [ 4 ]
#Text=In the Rump Parliament , Scobell found himself in the middle of the clashes leading to its dissolution in 1653 . [ 5 ]
#Text=He remained Clerk to Barebone 's Parliament . [ 6 ]
#Text=From 1655 Scobell became Clerk to the Council of State , a large jump in status , in succession to John Thurloe and sharing the position with William Jessop . [ 7 ]
#Text=Up to then he had been for a period an assistant secretary to the Council . [ 8 ]
#Text=In 1658 , as a preliminary to the Savoy Assembly , Scobell called together elders of Independent churches from the London area , in the house of George Griffith . [ 9 ]
#Text=He himself was an elder of the Congregational church of John Rowe , meeting in Westminster Abbey . [ 10 ]
#Text=In October 1659 he was one of those calling on George Monck to intervene in the vacuum of power after the death of Oliver Cromwell . [ 11 ]
